After publication, such an edition must have become the basis of all Plautina study‚ an assumption which accounts for the fact that all the other plays became scattered again and were gradually lost. The text of Plautus must, by this time, have become very cor- rupt. To render it readable, many arbitrary alterations were undoubtedly made3 to render it intelligible, frequent oom- ments and glosses were added. ln this way numerous inter- polations crept in, and the text became still further corrupted. It should be notioed, however, that the corruptions dating from this period are chiefly due to a lively interest in the plays, while the earlier corruptions above referred to (p. xxii) were due to carelessness and neglect.
